It seems to me we developed quantum mechanics as a statistical treatment of reality because
there was no way to deal with very large numbers of very small particles, whose motions
depend on on such a vast number of very small particles so small in size and in mass that they
are on the same order of the sizes and energies of particles we use to observer them, like
photons.!
Much in the same way, formulating a theory for the formation of the solar system becomes
vastly unmanageable, because for instance we have to solve Newtons Universal Law for the
gravitational interaction between billions of small grain sized dust particles and it, which is!
!
Becomes impossible to solve in general for the number of masses exceeding n=2, the so-
called N-Body problem.!
As such, I think it may be possible to gain some ground by using quantum mechanics wave
equation, but it has to be used dierently as used in quantum mechanics because the orbits of
the planets are very dierent in Nature than the orbits of say electrons around protons; planets
do not absorb energy from the sun, and as consequence jumps to another orbit, nor are they
so small and light that they are reasonably aected by an incident photon, let alone a large
amount of radiation. Reality at the quantum level is skitzy, like a dust particle in a tornado.!
However, all though the above equation cannot be solved algebraically for many bodies, I think
its solution may be in the wave equation in the sense that the orbits of the planets are like
frequencies in the sense that they complete revolutions around the sun in a constant amount of
time for each, and that, the planets are distributed as they are with these frequencies because
as such they dont interfere with one another gravitationally. That is they are where they are
because such interfering orbits became unstable and thus there is nothing where the planets
arent located.!

To do a thorough treatment of using the wave equation on things the sizes of planets, it would
be good to nd a constant that explains the relationship between things at the macrolevel like
Plancks constant does at the microlevel. Not just that, but characterize through these
constants the connection between the wave equation in the microcosmos and the wave
equation in the macrocosmos. And even nd a constant that characterizes the connection
between these two. Certainly Plancks constant would apply better to something like a dust
particle in a tornado, than it would to a planet orbiting the sun. Indeed we might say there is a
cosmos between an electron orbiting a proton and a planet orbiting the sun, that very realm of
a dust particle in a tornado, like Einsteins treatment of Brownian motion, a dust particle on the
surface of water being knocked around by the atoms that make up the water.!
Like this we can consider the action on a small grain like a grain of sand being aected by a
swirling protoplanetary disc; a problem of vorticity in vector calculus as applied to the wave
equation.!
The idea of a macrocosmos and a microcosmos has been explored down the generations.
Mark Twain comes to mind and his story of a science hobbiest who had a microscope, and,
who, one day when looking at a drop of water through it to study the various microscopic
organisms swimming around in it, was suddenly catapulted into it and found himself on a ship
where the microbes were now giant sea monsters with which he was battling for his life as he
tried to gure out how to get back to the macrocosmos. !
Indeed you will notice my equation loses ground at Neptune, but that is okay, because indeed
the planets do not continue to innity, as does the equation in an increasing fashion, but I feel it
is best to start there to get a rough sketch of the dynamics of the solar systems formation, and
then after that add the damping factor that makes it taper at the end."
